**Predictors of lamprey survival**

Neither fish length at the time of tagging nor handling time strongly influenced the survival probability of PIT tagged lamprey (Figures 2A-B). Fish of all sizes died as a result of the PIT tagging procedure (range: 76-148 mm); however, no fish tagged that was ~115 mm total length survived (Figure 2A). Additionally, there was little evidence

that handling time (seconds) had a strong influence of survival (Figure 2B). Any fish with comments such as &quot;rough insertion&quot; or &quot;big cut&quot; died, as did all of the lamprey that had their gut exposed.

**Influence of total length on life stage**

As we were tagging and measuring lamprey captured during the three-pass deletion efforts, we noticed many individuals that were clearly transitioning to the adult life-stage. Although total length was clearly a strong predictor of the probability that an individual was in the transforming life-stage (Figure 4), there must be additional environmental cues that influence lamprey development. A potential threshold length was evident since no individuals \&lt;120 mm were metamorphic (Figure 4); however, many larger individuals had not yet started transforming. We should start photographing each lamprey we capture to confirm our field life-stage designations and help us integrate additional variables into this analysis.
